    <p>After a surprisingly fulfilling binge of Avatar: The Last Airbender, I found myself searching for a bit more Avatar goodness to fill the void (no, the movie doesn't count). My friend informed me that Nickelodeon had, in fact, released a sequel to the show back in 2012, but warned me that it didn't quite reach the bar set by the original. </p>
    <p> I try to approach new shows, games, or really any media with an open mind, but this time around it's impossible to ignore the elephant in the room: Legend of Korra is the sequel to Avatar, and as such has some absurdly high standards to meet. I feel as if almost everyone who watches Korra will at least be somewhat familiar with The Last Airbender, and inevitably make comparisons, but I will do my best to discuss The Legend of Korra on its own merits.</p>

    <h1>A Strange Sense of Déjà Vu</h1>
    <br><b>(minor spoilers ahead by the way)</b>
    <p>Korra starts off about as one would expect - explaining the death of Aang and the rebirth of the new Avatar. The stage is set with the introduction of Republic City, a bastion of peace where citizens of all 4 nations come together and live in harmony. From there, we meet most of the main cast, and it's immediately clear that they've decided to stick with much of their old formula. You've got Mako and Bolin, the serious dad and the class clown, this show's "siblings who butt heads," whom often provide comedic relief. Asami is rich girl with daddy issues (Toph). Pabu is funny pet/Momo 2.0, while Naga, Korra's mount, is basically a less interesting version of Appa. The Avatar this time around is a 17-year-old water tribe girl, who is just as mischevious and carefree as Aang while being considerably more stubborn, impulsive, and down for violence than her predecessor.</p>
    <p>I can't help but feel like I've seen this before, except this time around the main cast falls a little flat. Mako and Bolin never really feel like they change or grow that much - they don't have any personal hardships to overcome, and end up feeling like very stagnant characters. Bolin is at least funny, but Mako has about as much charisma as a brick. The pair meet Korra at a professional bending tournament, and after they form a team and compete, the two of them kind of just...hang around. They always feel like they're just there, because it's a show and the Avatar needs homies. Not to mention their whole weird love triangle with Korra. I don't know who OK'd that idea, because all it did was make me go "huh?" and make Korra and Mako way less likeable.</p>
    <p> On the other hand, pretty much everybody else is fucking awesome. Aang's kids and grandkids are hilarious, and it's great to see how each of them inherited a little slice of his personality. Side characters like the eccentric scientist Varrick and his hapless assistant Zhu Li, who constantly has to put up with his bullshit, ended up being some of my favorites among the whole cast. A few familiar faces from The Last Airbender also make a return, and when they came on screen I was that Leonardo DiCaprio pointing meme, but for the most part they take a back seat and let the spotlight shine on the new cast.</p>
    <p>The villains range from really compelling to "what the fuck am I watching right now?" I really enjoyed getting to know the antagonists of Book 1 and 3, and even sympathized with them a little bit, but let's just say that Book 2 was so awful that I literally stopped watching the show for a few weeks.</p>

