    </div>

    <p>Herein lies The Legend of Korra's biggest problem: inconsistency. Book 1 is riveting and gripping, establishing the setting for the series, and the villain actually had a legitimate point to boot. Book 2 throws all that in the trash and tries to go full DBZ with spirit laser beams and shit. Real headscratcher. Then we hit Book 3, easily the strongest; Zaheer is a total badass and brings Korra some of her best fights. Everything's lined up for a fantastic finish, and Book 4 starts off strong but then kind of just runs out of gas and sputters to a halt. Not to mention the ending is literally just the Season 2 finale, except with a big metal robot instead. Really?</p>
    <p>Now, it's worth mentioning that this is partially Nickelodeon's fault. Apparently, the show was only approved for 1 season at a time, so the writers had to write and tie up each season assuming it was their last. Unsurprisingly, this resulted in 4 seasons that feel pretty much completely independent of each other, like 4 condensed short stories. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, especially when it comes to introducing new viewers to the show. But it does result in some wildly inconsistent quality and storytelling, with strange pacing that feels completely off as we skip months or sometimes even years between each book.</p>

    <h1>Silver Linings</h1>
    <p>I don't mean to give the impression that The Legend of Korra is shit, because it isn't. A perfect show it is not, but it succeeds on a few counts. The voice acting is spot on with big names like J.K. Simmons and Steve Blum, and the soundtrack I think actually one-ups its predecessor (especially that credits song, hot damn). I also think the animation is generally of a higher quality than before, and I found myself enjoying the new steampunk, neo-retro vibe of Republic City.</p>
    <p>The Legend of Korra also feels a bit more grown-up and mature. This time around, the show isn't strictly marketed towards 12-year-olds, so  they got free reign to discuss topics like discrimination, classism, political unrest, PTSD, and even some murder-suicide. Characters actually die on-screen for once. Fun stuff.  I think they depicted all of these issues in a very realistic and accurate manner, and they weren't forced to sugarcoat things for their younger audience like they had to before.</p> 
    <p>And much like the original Avatar, the writing and character development on display is (mostly) phenomenal. Tenzin, Aang's only airbending child, struggles with both living in the shadow of Aang's legacy and reviving the entire Air Nomad culture by himself. As a result of their chaotic childhood, Toph's kids hold a rocky relationship with both their estranged mother and each other, but eventually have to make amends to help each other out. Korra herself starts off as a reckless, punch-first-ask-questions-later hothead, and while I didn't like her at first she definitely grew on me. She matures, gets humbled, and eventually learns what being the Avatar is all about: keeping the peace.</p>

