    <h1>If It Ain't Broke...</h1>    
    <p>As a sequel, TLOK unsurprisingly builds upon the rules and universe established in the original show. Of course, I don't expect them to just keep everything the same, and build an exact replica of their previous work. But some of the stylistic changes they made rubbed me the wrong way.</p>
    <p>Let's start with the most obvious: <b>Bending.</b></p>
    <p> Bending seems to have simplified a lot this time around, and difficult/rare techniques like lightningbending are now so commonplace that Mako at one point literally gets a minimum wage job to shoot lightning at generators. Small details like this really cheapen the impact of bending, to the point where it feels pedestrian. In addition, gone are the distinct martial arts styles associated with each element. Instead, most fights in TLOK involve a bunch of people punching and kicking their respective elements at each other.</p>

    <div class="uc4polaroidsmall">
        <img src="../images/katarafight.gif" alt="ATLABfight" style ="width:100%">
        <div class="caption">I mean, just compare this...</div>
    </div>
    <div class="uc4polaroidsmall">
        <img src="../images/korrafight.gif" alt="TLOKfight" style ="width:100%">
        <div class="caption">To this...</div>
    </div>

    <p>I didn't realize how much I would miss this until it was gone. I hate to make comparisons again but fights in TLAB are so distinct, so visually obvious with who is participating and who is doing what, versus the Christmas-light-orgy that some Korra fights devolve into. We even got to see the benders learn from each other; late in the first show we saw Zuko use a breakdance spin kick (one of Aang's airbending moves), a defensive Earth-based stance to part a wall of fire, and lightning redirection (a waterbender based move Iroh taught him).</p>
    <p>We see a little bit of this in Book 1 of Korra, when they're playing in the pro bending tournament, and their opponents illegally mix elements against them. But the concept is dropped shortly after, and while the sub-genres of bending (metalbending, lavabending, bloodbending) are explored more in-depth, overall the quality of fights in Korra is lower.</p>

    <p>My biggest issue, however, is with the Avatar herself, and the Avatar State. While I do think Korra is a well-written, relatable character who undergoes significant growth, she never actually feels that powerful. When you're the fucking <i>Avatar,</i> the most powerful bender on Earth, essentially a demi-god, and also the <i>protagonist of the show</i>, I don't feel like it's unreasonable to want to see Korra bash some heads, right?</p>
    <p>Korra never seems to become a stronger bender or fighter. The obligatory recap episode before the grand finale really highlights this: as Korra narrates everything she's been through in the past 4 seasons, it's literally just a montage of her getting her ass kicked by various bad guys. Why does she never get her big moment, her no-holds-barred-lets-fuck-shit-up that really makes a protagonist feel badass?</p>
    <p>This issue becomes most glaring when it comes to The Avatar State. Korra feels like she gets a minor power boost every time she does it, and she uses it so often that it quickly loses any importance. I mean, early on she literally Avatar States just to win a race against children. Again, don't mean to compare, but Aang was so powerful and destructive in the Avatar State that he was genuinely afraid of it and himself, and spent much of the show coming to terms with it. It felt so much more impactful when it did come up that it felt like a significant plot point, and gave room for Aang's character to grow.</p>


    <h1>Verdict</h1>
    <p>It was much harder for me to get invested into The Legend of Korra. I mentioned before that I had to take a break halfway through the show, and the sudden whiplash change in quality made me not want to continue watching. I'm glad I did, because I do think Korra is not a bad show. It's got great moments, and some episodes that are on par with the quality of The Last Airbender. However, it's certainly not as polished.</p>
    <p>Is Korra a good show on it's own? Yeah, I think so. It's inconsistent for sure, but the good moments outweigh the bad, and overall I liked most of the cast enough to keep me hooked 'til the end. </p>
    <p>Is Korra a worthy successor to The Last Airbender? Probably not, honestly. Personally I think the original is a much better watch all the way through, but both shows have great moments that easily rival the other. </p>
    <p>I give The Legend of Korra a solid 7/10. If anything, if you're thinking of watching this series I would just skip Book 2 because it's complete ass, everything else ranges from decent to actually really good.</p>
